"name":"Rochfort","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Niall.","English: variant of   Ratchford  .","Irish: of Norman origin, probably brought to Ireland by the Normans after 1171, when Henry II acquired Dublin. However, it is not known if it was an English name (see   Ratchford  ), or a Norman equivalent of the French name   Rochefort  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rockford","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Rochford   or   Ratchford  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Rachford","meanings":["English:","variant of   Rochford  .","variant of<b>Rackford</b>, a habitational name from Rackenford in Devon,recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Racheneforda</i>, which Millsinterprets as ‘ford suitable for riding, by a stretch of river’."]},{"name":"Ratchford","meanings":["habitational name from Rochford (Worcestershire), from Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’ (genitive <i>ræcces</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","habitational name from Rochford (Essex). Early forms of the name ending in <i>Ro-</i> suggest that the placename derives from Old English <i>hrōc</i> ‘rook’ or the Old English personal name <i>Hrōc(a)</i> + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, but the 13th century forms in <i>Ra-</i> and <i>Re-</i> suggest that the first element is Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’.","English:"]},{"name":"Rotchford","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin.","Irish and English: variant of   Rochford  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Rochfort was born about 1300, in County Meath, Ireland as the son of Milo De Rochfort and Mrs. Milo De Rochfort. He married Eglentina about 1325, in County Westmeath, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1346, at the age of 48."},"et":{"about 1300–C 1346":"umbes 1300–umbes 1346","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1326–Male":"1326–Surnud","1328–1349":"1328–1349","1272–1309":"1272–1309","–Female":"Surnud","ABT 1325":"umbes 1325","1272":"1272","Abt 1328":"umbes 1328","C 1346":"umbes 1346","1349":"1349","1326":"1326","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","after 1309":"pärast 1309","about 1326":"umbes 1326","1298":"1298","about 1300":"umbes 1300","about 1297":"umbes 1297","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","Of Kilbridge, West Meath, Ire":"County Westmeath, Iirimaa","Kilbride, County Meath, Ireland":"Kilbride, County Meath, Iirimaa","County Meath, Ireland":"County Meath, Iirimaa","Of Kilbridge, West Meath, Ireland":"County Westmeath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1300–C 1346":"noin 1300–noin 1346","1298–Male":"1298–Kuollut","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1304–Female":"1304–Kuollut","1326–Male":"1326–Kuollut","1328–1349":"1328–1349","1272–1309":"1272–1309","–Female":"Kuollut","ABT 1325":"noin 1325","1272":"1272","Abt 1328":"noin 1328","C 1346":"noin 1346","1349":"1349","1326":"1326","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","after 1309":"1309 jälkeen","about 1326":"noin 1326","1298":"1298","about 1300":"noin 1300","about 1297":"noin 1297","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","Of Kilbridge, West 